r parties; the success or failure of policies advocated by parties; or alterations in parties’ positions on key issues. They contend that, while all three factors contribute, it is the latter, a party changing positions on a chief concern, that most consistently leads voters to or from a particular party. Their approach provides a deeper knowledge of the critical moving parts in democratic politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aComparative government. 0aParty affiliationzAustralia. 0aParty affiliationzCanada. 0aParty affiliationzGreat Britain. 0aParty affiliationzUnited States. 0aParty affiliation. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aJackson, John E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMann Levesque, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073919040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226762531423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226762531/original  a978-3-11-073919-0  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles